            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "wow thanks! that's the way i should have know before i open this issue.\r\n\r\nthough i found  a case `winnr('#')` does not fit well which is not a real problem in most time: the returned winnr will always be in the same tabpage, and that's why it's named `winnr` of course.\r\n\r\nsay there is a tabpage#1 which has a winid#1000, a tabpage#2 which has a winid#1001, we are in winid#1000, and `:lua vim.api.nvim_set_current_win(10001)` will get we to tabpage#2 winid#1001, so now the previous window would be 1000.\r\n(i'm not sure if it's worth to consider such case, i just realized it.)",
